Here's the recommended approach using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In `App.xaml.cs`** — override `CreateWindow` and hook `Stopped`, `Resumed`, and `Destroying`:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Stopped += (s, e) => SaveDraft();
        window.Resumed += (s, e) => RestoreDraft();
        window.Destroying += (s, e) => SaveDraft(); // Android back-button skips Stopped

        return window;
    }

    private void SaveDraft()
    {
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.ViewModel.DraftText);
        }
    }

    private void RestoreDraft()
    {
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
        {
            page.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        }
    }
}
```

**In your ViewModel** — restore on initial load too:

```csharp
public partial class NoteViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string draftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
}
```

### Key points

| Concern | Why |
|---|---|
| Save in **`Stopped`** | Fires when the app is fully backgrounded |
| Save in **`Destroying`** too | Android back-button can skip `Stopped` entirely |
| Restore in **`Resumed`** | Fires when returning from background |
| Use **`Preferences`** | Fast & synchronous — avoids ANR/watchdog kills (keep handlers under ~2s) |
| Don't save in `Deactivated` | That fires for notification shade, split-screen, etc. — not a true background |
| Don't use `OnSleep`/`OnResume` | Legacy Xamarin methods; bypass window-level events |
